      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20
Yesterday Twitter Inc.  sued Elon Musk=C2=A0in Delaware to hold him to his =
agreement to buy Twitter for $54.20 per share. Twitter=E2=80=99s lawyers ar=
e=C2=A0hoping for  a quick trial=C2=A0in September, so that the deal can cl=
ose on schedule in October.[1] You can read Twitter=E2=80=99s complaint her=
e. Here=E2=80=99s the gist of it:Having mounted a public spectacle to put T=
witter in play, and having proposed and then signed a seller-friendly merge=
r agreement, Musk apparently believes that he =E2=80=94 unlike every other =
party subject to Delaware contract law =E2=80=94 is free to change his mind=
, trash the company, disrupt its operations, destroy stockholder value, and=
=C2=A0walk away. This repudiation follows a long list of material contractu=
al breaches by Musk that have cast a pall over Twitter and its business. Tw=
itter brings this action to enjoin Musk from further breaches, to compel Mu=
sk to fulfill his legal obligations, and to compel consummation of the merg=
er upon satisfaction of the few outstanding conditions.If you  have been  f=
ollowing the Musk/Twitter fight, here at Money Stuff or otherwise, nothing =
in this complaint will be a huge surprise to you. On the other hand if you =
have been following the Musk/Twitter fight, it is probably because you are =
interested in that fight, and if you are interested in that fight then Twit=
ter=E2=80=99s lawsuit against Musk will probably be of interest to you. So =
I guess we should go through the complaint.=C2=A0The basic narrative beats =
will be familiar. Musk secretly=C2=A0bought a 9.1% stake in Twitter,=C2=A0v=
iolating securities laws in the process,=C2=A0then announced that stake and=
 agitated to join Twitter=E2=80=99s board:Starting in January 2022, Musk be=
gan purchasing Twitter stock. By March 14, 2022, he had secretly accumulate=
d a substantial position =E2=80=94 about 5% of the company=E2=80=99s outsta=
nding shares. SEC regulations required that he disclose that position no la=
ter than March 24, 2022. Musk failed to disclose, and instead kept amassing=
 Twitter stock with the market none the wiser. By April 1, 2022, Musk had a=
ccumulated about 9.1% of the company=E2=80=99s outstanding shares, still in=
 secret. ...Meanwhile, on March 26, 2022, Musk spoke with two Twitter direc=
tors, Jack Dorsey and Egon Durban, about the future of social media and the=
 prospect of Musk=E2=80=99s joining the Twitter board. Soon after, Musk tol=
d Twitter CEO Parag Agrawal and Twitter board chair Bret Taylor that he had=
 in mind three options relative to Twitter: join its board, take the compan=
y private, or start a competitor.So he signed an agreement to join Twitter=
=E2=80=99s board, then changed his mind and  backed out of the agreement. I=
nstead, he sent Twitter a take-it-or-leave-it unsolicited offer to buy the =
company for $54.20 per share in cash, and tweeted some cryptic threats to l=
aunch a tender offer if Twitter=E2=80=99s board didn=E2=80=99t sell. He als=
o  lined up committed financing from banks. So Twitter=E2=80=99s board nego=
tiated a merger agreement with Musk, and they=C2=A0signed it on April 25.Th=
en the stock market went down:The risk of market decline, which was Musk=E2=
=80=99s alone to bear under the merger agreement, materialized. Soon after =
signing, the U.S. capital markets took a turn for the worse. Within a week =
after April 25, 2022, the date the merger agreement was executed, Musk elec=
ted to sell 9.8 million Tesla shares to finance the merger at prices as low=
 as $822.68 per share, substantially below their pre-Twitter-signing price =
of $1,005 per share.=C2=A0So Musk tried to find some pretext to get out of =
the deal:Musk wanted an escape. But the merger agreement left him little ro=
om. With no financing contingency or diligence condition, the agreement gav=
e Musk no out absent a Company Material Adverse Effect or a material covena=
nt breach by Twitter. Musk had to try to conjure one of those.And because h=
e is Elon Musk,  he chose the=C2=A0most ridiculous imaginable pretext:=C2=
=A0What Musk alighted upon first was a representation in Twitter=E2=80=99s =
quarterly SEC filings over many consecutive years that based on its interna=
l=C2=A0processes the company estimated =E2=80=9Cthe average of false or spa=
m accounts=E2=80=9D on its platform =E2=80=9Crepresented fewer than 5% of o=
ur mDAU during the quarter.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CMonetizable Daily Active Usag=
e or Users,=E2=80=9D or mDAU, is a non-GAAP metric Twitter employs to measu=
re the number of people or organizations that use the Twitter platform. =E2=
=80=A6Twitter=E2=80=99s SEC disclosures regarding that process and its find=
ings are heavily qualified. As described in the =E2=80=9CNote Regarding Key=
 Metrics=E2=80=9D section of its filings, Twitter=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ccalcul=
ation of mDAU is not based on any standardized industry methodology,=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9Cmay differ from estimates published by third parties or from s=
imilarly-titled metrics of our competitors,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cmay not a=
ccurately reflect the actual number of people or organizations using our pl=
atform.=E2=80=9D As for the estimate of spam or false accounts as a percent=
age of mDAU, Twitter explains that it is=C2=A0based on =E2=80=9Can internal=
 review of a sample of accounts,=E2=80=9D involves =E2=80=9Csignificant jud=
gment,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cmay not accurately represent the actual number of =
[false or spam] accounts,=E2=80=9D and could be too low. Twitter has publis=
